**useEffect** runs side effects after the component renders.

**Syntax:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
    // Effect code
}, [dependencies]);
```

**Three dependency array scenarios:**

**1. No array — Runs after EVERY render:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
    console.log('Runs after every render');
});
// Use case: Rare, usually a mistake
```

**2. Empty array `[]` — Runs ONCE (on mount):**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
    console.log('Runs only once when component mounts');
    // Fetch initial data, set up subscriptions
}, []);
// Use case: Initial data fetching, subscriptions
```

**3. With dependencies `[count]` — Runs when dependencies change:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
    console.log('Runs when count changes');
    document.title = `Count: ${count}`;
}, [count]);
// Use case: React to specific value changes
```

**Complete example:**
```tsx
function Example() {
    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
    const [name, setName] = useState('');

    // Runs on every render
    useEffect(() => {
        console.log('Every render');
    });

    // Runs once on mount
    useEffect(() => {
        console.log('Component mounted');
        // Fetch initial data
    }, []);

    // Runs when count changes
    useEffect(() => {
        console.log('Count changed:', count);
    }, [count]);

    // Runs when count OR name changes
    useEffect(() => {
        console.log('Count or name changed');
    }, [count, name]);

    return <div>...</div>;
}
```

**Rule:** Always include values from component scope (props, state) used inside the effect in the dependency array.

```tsx
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function UserProfile({ userId }) {
    const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
    const [error, setError] = useState(null);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Can't make useEffect callback async directly
        const fetchUser = async () => {
            try {
                // Reset states
                setLoading(true);
                setError(null);

                // Fetch data
                const response = await fetch(
                    `https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/${userId}`
                );

                // Check if response is ok
                if (!response.ok) {
                    throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
                }

                // Parse JSON
                const data = await response.json();
                setUser(data);
            } catch (err) {
                // Handle errors
                setError(err.message);
                setUser(null);
            } finally {
                // Always runs (success or error)
                setLoading(false);
            }
        };

        fetchUser();
    }, [userId]); // Re-fetch when userId changes

    // Loading state
    if (loading) {
        return (
            <div className="loading">
                <div className="spinner"></div>
                <p>Loading user...</p>
            </div>
        );
    }

    // Error state
    if (error) {
        return (
            <div className="error">
                <p>❌ Error: {error}</p>
                <button onClick={() => window.location.reload()}>
                    Try Again
                </button>
            </div>
        );
    }

    // Success state
    if (!user) {
        return <div>No user found</div>;
    }

    return (
        <div className="user-profile">
            <h2>{user.name}</h2>
            <p><strong>Email:</strong> {user.email}</p>
            <p><strong>Phone:</strong> {user.phone}</p>
            <p><strong>Website:</strong> {user.website}</p>
            <div className="address">
                <h3>Address</h3>
                <p>{user.address.street}, {user.address.city}</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    );
}

export default UserProfile;
```

**Key points:**

✅ Three states: loading, error, data
✅ try/catch/finally for error handling
✅ async function created inside useEffect
✅ Conditional rendering based on state
✅ Re-fetches when userId changes

A **cleanup function** runs when:
1. Component unmounts
2. Before the effect runs again (if dependencies changed)

It prevents **memory leaks** and **unwanted behavior**.

**Syntax:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
    // Setup

    return () => {
        // Cleanup (runs on unmount or before re-run)
    };
}, []);
```

**Example 1: Timer (setInterval)**

```tsx
function Timer() {
    const [seconds, setSeconds] = useState(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Setup: Start interval
        const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
            setSeconds(prev => prev + 1);
        }, 1000);

        // ✅ Cleanup: Clear interval
        return () => {
            clearInterval(intervalId);
            console.log('Timer cleaned up');
        };
    }, []);

    return <div>Seconds: {seconds}</div>;
}
```

Without cleanup, interval keeps running even after component unmounts → memory leak!

**Example 2: Event Listener**

```tsx
function MouseTracker() {
    const [position, setPosition] = useState({ x: 0, y: 0 });

    useEffect(() => {
        const handleMouseMove = (e) => {
            setPosition({ x: e.clientX, y: e.clientY });
        };

        // Setup: Add listener
        window.addEventListener('mousemove', handleMouseMove);

        // ✅ Cleanup: Remove listener
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('mousemove', handleMouseMove);
        };
    }, []);

    return <div>Mouse: {position.x}, {position.y}</div>;
}
```

**Example 3: Fetch with AbortController**

```tsx
function UserData({ userId }) {
    const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

    useEffect(() => {
        const abortController = new AbortController();

        const fetchUser = async () => {
            try {
                const response = await fetch(
                    `https://api.example.com/users/${userId}`,
                    { signal: abortController.signal } // Pass abort signal
                );
                const data = await response.json();
                setUser(data);
            } catch (error) {
                if (error.name !== 'AbortError') {
                    console.error('Error:', error);
                }
            }
        };

        fetchUser();

        // ✅ Cleanup: Abort fetch if userId changes or unmounts
        return () => {
            abortController.abort();
        };
    }, [userId]);

    return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

**Common cleanup scenarios:**

| Effect | Cleanup |
|--------|----------|
| `setInterval` | `clearInterval(id)` |
| `setTimeout` | `clearTimeout(id)` |
| Event listeners | `removeEventListener` |
| Fetch requests | `abortController.abort()` |
| WebSocket | `socket.close()` |
| Subscriptions | `unsubscribe()` |

**Lifting state up** means moving state to the closest common parent component so multiple children can access and modify it.

**Problem:** Sibling components can't directly share state.

**Example: Product List and Cart**

```tsx
// ❌ PROBLEM: ProductList and Cart can't communicate
function App() {
    return (
        <div>
            <ProductList />  {/* Has products */}
            <Cart />         {/* Needs to know what's added */}
        </div>
    );
}
```

**✅ SOLUTION: Lift state to parent**

```tsx
import { useState } from 'react';

// Parent component holds shared state
function App() {
    const [cart, setCart] = useState([]);

    const addToCart = (product) => {
        setCart([...cart, product]);
    };

    const removeFromCart = (productId) => {
        setCart(cart.filter(item => item.id !== productId));
    };

    return (
        <div className="app">
            {/* Pass state and functions down as props */}
            <ProductList onAddToCart={addToCart} />
            <Cart items={cart} onRemoveFromCart={removeFromCart} />
        </div>
    );
}

// Child 1: ProductList
function ProductList({ onAddToCart }) {
    const products = [
        { id: 1, name: 'Laptop', price: 999 },
        { id: 2, name: 'Phone', price: 699 },
        { id: 3, name: 'Tablet', price: 499 }
    ];

    return (
        <div className="product-list">
            <h2>Products</h2>
            {products.map(product => (
                <div key={product.id} className="product">
                    <h3>{product.name}</h3>
                    <p>${product.price}</p>
                    <button onClick={() => onAddToCart(product)}>
                        Add to Cart
                    </button>
                </div>
            ))}
        </div>
    );
}

// Child 2: Cart
function Cart({ items, onRemoveFromCart }) {
    const total = items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);

    return (
        <div className="cart">
            <h2>Cart ({items.length})</h2>
            {items.length === 0 ? (
                <p>Cart is empty</p>
            ) : (
                <div>
                    {items.map((item, index) => (
                        <div key={index} className="cart-item">
                            <span>{item.name} - ${item.price}</span>
                            <button onClick={() => onRemoveFromCart(item.id)}>
                                Remove
                            </button>
                        </div>
                    ))}
                    <div className="total">
                        <strong>Total: ${total}</strong>
                    </div>
                </div>
            )}
        </div>
    );
}
```

**Key concept:**

1. **State lives in parent** (App)
2. **Children receive data via props** (cart items)
3. **Children call functions to update parent state** (addToCart, removeFromCart)
4. **Data flows down, events flow up**

**When to lift state:**

✅ Multiple components need the same data
✅ Sibling components need to communicate
✅ Data needs to be synchronized across components

**Problem with deep nesting:**

If state needs to be passed through many levels, consider:
- Context API (for global state like theme, user)
- State management libraries (Redux, Zustand)

```tsx
// hooks/useFetch.js
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function useFetch(url, options = {}) {
    const [data, setData] = useState(null);
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
    const [error, setError] = useState(null);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Don't fetch if no URL
        if (!url) return;

        const abortController = new AbortController();

        const fetchData = async () => {
            try {
                setLoading(true);
                setError(null);

                const response = await fetch(url, {
                    ...options,
                    signal: abortController.signal
                });

                if (!response.ok) {
                    throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
                }

                const result = await response.json();
                setData(result);
            } catch (err) {
                // Ignore abort errors
                if (err.name !== 'AbortError') {
                    setError(err.message);
                }
            } finally {
                setLoading(false);
            }
        };

        fetchData();

        // Cleanup: abort fetch on unmount or URL change
        return () => {
            abortController.abort();
        };
    }, [url]); // Re-fetch when URL changes

    return { data, loading, error };
}

export default useFetch;
```

**Usage in components:**

```tsx
import useFetch from './hooks/useFetch';

// Example 1: Fetch users
function UserList() {
    const { data: users, loading, error } = useFetch(
        'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users'
    );

    if (loading) return <div>Loading users...</div>;
    if (error) return <div>Error: {error}</div>;

    return (
        <ul>
            {users.map(user => (
                <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
            ))}
        </ul>
    );
}

// Example 2: Fetch single user
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
    const { data: user, loading, error } = useFetch(
        `https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/${userId}`
    );

    if (loading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
    if (error) return <div>Error: {error}</div>;
    if (!user) return <div>No user found</div>;

    return (
        <div>
            <h2>{user.name}</h2>
            <p>{user.email}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

// Example 3: Multiple fetches
function Dashboard() {
    const { data: users } = useFetch('https://api.example.com/users');
    const { data: posts } = useFetch('https://api.example.com/posts');
    const { data: comments } = useFetch('https://api.example.com/comments');

    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Dashboard</h1>
            <p>Users: {users?.length}</p>
            <p>Posts: {posts?.length}</p>
            <p>Comments: {comments?.length}</p>
        </div>
    );
}
```

**Enhanced version with refetch:**

```tsx
function useFetch(url, options = {}) {
    const [data, setData] = useState(null);
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
    const [error, setError] = useState(null);
    const [refetchIndex, setRefetchIndex] = useState(0);

    const refetch = () => {
        setRefetchIndex(prev => prev + 1);
    };

    useEffect(() => {
        const fetchData = async () => {
            // ... (same as before)
        };

        fetchData();
    }, [url, refetchIndex]); // Re-fetch when refetchIndex changes

    return { data, loading, error, refetch };
}

// Usage
function UserList() {
    const { data: users, loading, error, refetch } = useFetch(
        'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users'
    );

    return (
        <div>
            <button onClick={refetch}>Refresh</button>
            {/* ... */}
        </div>
    );
}
```

**Benefits of custom hooks:**

✅ Reusable logic
✅ Cleaner components
✅ Separation of concerns
✅ Easier testing
✅ Consistent error handling
